Why do we need this specific change when we already have "dump state port <interface name>" and "dump state portchannel"?
https://github.com/Azure/sonic-utilities/pull/1853
https://github.com/Azure/sonic-utilities/pull/1667

> Why do we need this specific change when we already have "dump state port " and "dump state portchannel"? #1853 #1667

The interface is a separate table in config_db and it is different from port which is for the physical port attributes and portchannel which is for LAG's properties

> #!/bin/bash

This issue is that "saisdkdump is not designed to run in paralell" and this is a platform specific issue. Why not let saisdkdump limit itself? It will not impact other platforms.

---
Refers to: scripts/generate_dump:1 in 0e896b5. [](commit_id = 0e896b5d159729f4a5e5864b3455033f33b42516, deletion_comment = False)

> > #!/bin/bash
> 
> This issue is that "saisdkdump is not designed to run in paralell" and this is a platform specific issue. Why not let saisdkdump limit itself? It will not impact other platforms.
> 
> Refers to: scripts/generate_dump:1 in [0e896b5](https://github.com/Azure/sonic-utilities/commit/0e896b5d159729f4a5e5864b3455033f33b42516). [](commit_id = [0e896b5](https://github.com/Azure/sonic-utilities/commit/0e896b5d159729f4a5e5864b3455033f33b42516), deletion_comment = False)

But which use case has the requirement to run multiple techsupports? Also with the auto-techsupport in place and to keep CPU usage in check, it is imperative that this locking is required.

> > #!/bin/bash

> In reply to: [1053794730](https://github.com/Azure/sonic-utilities/pull/2065#issuecomment-1053794730)
> 
> Refers to: scripts/generate_dump:1 in [0e896b5](https://github.com/Azure/sonic-utilities/commit/0e896b5d159729f4a5e5864b3455033f33b42516). [](commit_id = [0e896b5](https://github.com/Azure/sonic-utilities/commit/0e896b5d159729f4a5e5864b3455033f33b42516), deletion_comment = False)

saisdkdump is one reason. But as i've said, without locking there is always a possibility of multiple techsupport processes running in paralell. This is unnecessary from a functional standpoint and can also cause high CPU load. So, i don't see why this shouldn't be implemented.
